<br>
Supplies<br>
<br>
Steak (any cut will do really)<br>
Kosher salt<br>
Pepper<br>
Olive oil or vegetable oil<br>
Cast iron skillet<br>
<br>
Preparation<br>
<br>
(1) Take the steaks out of the fridge and let them warm up a bit.<br>
<br>
(2) Preheat the oven to 500 degrees with the iron skillet in there.<br>
<br>
(3) Take whatever oil you have decided upon and lightly rub it on both sides of your steak so that it is coated.<br>
<br>
(4) Sprinkle kosher salt on both sides of the steak.  You don’t want to put too much but you want to be able to see it on there.  Also throw on a dash or 2 of pepper depending upon how much you like pepper.<br>
<br>
(5) Turn on your stove top burner to high.<br>
<br>
Cooking<br>
<br>
(1) Once the oven has come to 500 degrees take out iron skillet out and put it on the burner.<br>
<br>
(2) Throw the steak into the skillet and sear one side for about 60 seconds.  You know when that side is appropriately seared cause you can pull the corner of the steak from the pan with out it sticking.<br>
<br>
(3) Flip the steak over and sear the other side for 60 seconds or so.  <br>
<br>
(4) Next throw the whole thing back into the oven which you left at 500 degrees.  <br>
<br>
(5) The length of time you keep the steak in the oven really depends on the thickness of the steak and how you like your steak cooked.  I like mine medium rare to medium so I usually cook an average size steak for another 5 minutes in the oven flipping the steak at the half way point.<br>
<br>
(6) Once the steak is cooked to your desired doneness it is imperative that you let the steak settle on top of something.  You see, this method has produced a very nice outer crust on your steak and if you through it on your plate and go at it all the excess juices in the steak that haven’t settled will drain out and form a pool around your steak utterly destroying the crust.  What I usually do is turn a ramekin or small bowl upside down on a plate and put the steak on the bottom of the overturned bowl.  This way the juices drain off.<br>
<br>
Advanced<br>
<br>
For you advanced cooks, wait to salt and pepper one of steak’s sides until you are actually searing the other side in the pan.  This way your salt and pepper won’t have been sitting around on the steak for long and flipped over a lot; thus producing an even better crust.<br>
